    "summary": "The Hubble Space Telescope was launched into low Earth orbit on April 24, 1990, aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery, becoming the first major space-based optical telescope. Named for astronomer Edwin Hubble, it was designed to observe the universe free from the distorting effects of Earth's atmosphere. However, a flaw in the primary mirror — a spherical aberration caused by a polishing error of only 1.3 micrometers — produced blurred images that initially appeared to doom the mission.\n\nA dramatic servicing mission in December 1993 installed corrective optics and restored Hubble's full capabilities. The repaired telescope produced images of extraordinary clarity and beauty that transformed both scientific astronomy and public engagement with space science. Among its most significant scientific contributions: deep field images revealing thousands of ancient galaxies in tiny patches of sky, providing evidence for the accelerating expansion of the universe and the existence of dark energy; observations that helped establish the age of the universe at approximately 13.8 billion years; and detailed studies of black holes, stellar nurseries, and planetary systems.\n\nHubble's iconic images became a cultural phenomenon, widely reproduced and exhibited as aesthetic objects independent of their scientific content. The telescope remained operational into the 2020s after multiple servicing missions and became one of the most productive scientific instruments ever built.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope",
